Cement Makers, Bharti, Coal India, IDFC: India Stocks Preview

-- B y   K a r t i k   G o y a l   a n d   S h i k h a r   B a l w a n i
-- 
2011-09-21T03:34:46Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-20/bharti-coal-india-sun-pharmaceutical-india-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes in  India  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and share prices are as of the last close.  The Bombay Stock Exchange Sensitive Index, or Sensex, rose
353.93, or 2.1 percent, to 17,099.28. The S&P CNX Nifty Index on
the National Stock Exchange added 2.2 percent to 5,140.20. The
BSE 200 Index increased 1.8 percent to 2,114.42. SGX S&P CNX
Nifty Index futures for September delivery slid 0.4 percent to
5,149 as of 11:29 a.m. in  Singapore .  Cement makers:  ACC Ltd. (ACC)   was raised to “buy” from
“hold” at Deutsche Bank by equity analyst Chockalingam
Narayanan with a price estimate of 1,180 rupees per share. The
brokerage raised Ambuja Cements Ltd. (ACEM IN) to “hold” from
“sell” with a 12-month price estimate of 137 rupees per share.  ACC rose 1.6 percent to 1,066.7 rupees. Ambuja gained 1.6
percent to 146.65 rupees.  Carmakers: Carmakers cut production during the festival
season for the first time in a decade as rising interest rates
and fuel prices have led to a pileup of unsold vehicles.  Maruti
Suzuki India Ltd. (MSIL)  , the nation’s largest carmaker,  Tata
Motors Ltd. (TTMT)  , and  South Korea ’s Hyundai Motor Co. have
scaled down production, the Economic Times reported, citing
component suppliers it didn’t identify.  Maruti rose 1.2 percent to 1,154.95 rupees. Tata Motors
jumped 2.8 percent to 166.2 rupees.  Bharti Airtel Ltd. (BHARTI)  : The Zambian unit of India’s
biggest mobile-network operator increased its mobile-phone
subscribers to 4 million from 3.8 million in July, Fayaz King,
managing director of Airtel Zambia, said in an interview on the
Lusaka-based Radio Phoenix yesterday. Shares of Bharti Airtel
rose 1.2 percent to 391.4 rupees.  Coal India Ltd. (COAL)  : A group of Indian ministers
agreed to allow companies to seek approval to mine coal in some
dense forest areas, overturning an environment ministry ban,
according to two government officials. The decision will benefit
companies including Coal India and  Hindalco Industries Ltd. (HNDL) 
. Shares of Coal India rose 0.5 percent to 378.4
rupees. Hindalco Industries jumped 4.1 percent to 150.05 rupees.  Infrastructure Development Finance Co. (IDFC IN): The
Indian lender to power and road projects will acquire an IT park
jointly owned by  DLF Ltd. (DLFU)   and The 3C Company in Noida
for 5.12 billion rupees, The Economic Times reported, citing a
person it didn’t identify. IDFC shares climbed 1.9 percent to
115.2 rupees while DLF’s rallied 3.4 percent to 212.15 rupees.  Housing Development & Infrastructure Ltd. (HDIL)  : The
real estate developer has put nearly 5 million square feet of
land parcels at Virar, near Mumbai, on the block, The Economic
Times reported, citing people it didn’t identify. HDIL expects
to raise 6.50 billion rupees through the sale in the next few
weeks to repay its debt, the report said. Shares gained 1.3
percent to 112.4 rupees.  KS Oils Ltd. (KSO)  : The founders of the Indian rapeseed
oil processor may face obstacles in their plans to sell the
company as accounting issues and a possible loss of around 4
billion rupees deters buyers, The Economic Times reported,
citing three people it didn’t identify. Shares were unchanged at
12.35 rupees.  Larsen & Toubro Ltd. (LT)  : India’s defense ministry has
recommended the country’s biggest engineering company as the
preferred partner for state-run Hindustan Shipyard, Business
Standard reported, citing people it didn’t identify. Larsen’s
stock added 0.1 percent to 1,562.9 rupees.  Sun Pharmaceutical Industries Ltd. (SUNP)  : The drugmaker
was rated “neutral” in new coverage by Princy Singh, an equity
analyst at JPMorgan Chase & Co. The analyst has a share-price
forecast of 510 rupees. The shares gained 2.3 percent to 484.4
rupees.  Welspun Corp. (WLCO IN): The Indian pipe maker’s unit
Welspun Infratech bought a 50 percent stake in a 4 billion-rupee
project being developed by ARSS Infrastructure Projects Ltd.,
the Economic Times reported, citing Welspun group’s Chairman
B.K. Goenka. Welspun Corp. shares added 0.9 percent to 124.9
rupees.  To contact the reporters on this story:
